data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` ŌĆö now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire expression-tree construction can be replaced:

```csharp
// EF Core 10 ŌĆö simple lambda with conditionals
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The `Action<...>` signature replaces `Expression<Func<...>>`, so the old `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` code **won't compile** anymore. The good news: the replacement is dramatically simpler.

---

### 2. Complex type column names ŌĆö uniquified & nested paths changed

Two changes apply:

**a) Duplicate property names across complex types get a numeric suffix.** Since both `ShippingAddress` and `BillingAddress` have a `Street` property, EF 10 will auto-uniquify them (e.g., `Street` vs `Street1`). A migration will try to rename columns.

**b) Nested complex types now include the full path.** Your `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` column changes from `BillingAddress_City` ŌåÆ `Payment_BillingAddress_City`.

**Fix:** Pin the old column names explicitly so no migration rename is generated:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
        // ... other properties
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types, pin the old name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

After configuring, run `dotnet ef migrations add VerifyNoChanges` ŌĆö it should produce an empty migration if the names are pinned correctly.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` ŌĆö new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gains a `string logCommandText` parameter (redacted SQL safe for logging). Your implementation won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ŌåÉ new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) ŌĆö they all received the same new parameter.
